The Lantern Reforms were Midgaard's second major governance layer, added during the Standardization Century when population growth outpaced the First Stone Accord's militia-and-tribunal framework.
Named for the lamp-lines system — standardized oil lanterns posted at regular intervals along primary corridors and watched-square perimeters — the Reforms made Midgaard's governance physically legible to strangers.
The core innovations were: standardized paving marks (symbols identifying road type and jurisdiction), posted tariffs (fixed rates displayed at trade entry points), district lamp-lines (the lantern network defining where civic obligation applied), and rotating night patrol routes tied to lantern station intervals.
Each lantern station created an administrative node: a posted notice point, a patrol rendezvous, and a visible marker of where watched-square security extended.
The Reforms were driven by a practical problem: merchants from multiple origins needed to navigate Midgaard's dispute system, and the system was not legible to people who did not already know its oral traditions.
Standardization was security infrastructure — merchants who could not read the system could not comply with it, and non-compliance created friction that the militia system had to resolve through force rather than procedure.
The Lantern Reforms' lamp-lines are the origin of the folk belief that "Midgaard never stops watching" — the city that maintains visible light through every night as a continuous assertion of civic order.
The Reforms introduced the district concept: defined territories with specific administrative oversight, distinct from the earlier ward-captain system's informal boundaries.
District boundaries were set to correspond to existing commercial patterns rather than geographic features, which is why Midgaard's district map looks arbitrary from the outside but makes sense from the merchant's perspective.
The lamp-lines system was also the first infrastructure capable of transmitting emergency signals: lanterns unlit, lit in sequence, or lit in specific combinations communicated gate-closure, fire-alarm, or tribunal-assembly calls across the city without requiring messengers.
The Lantern Reforms' physical infrastructure — the lamp-lines, paving marks, and posted notice boards — survived into every subsequent governance layer and are still visible in Midgaard's street design.

