The Reforms codified the distinction between commercial law (tariff compliance, contract registration) and civic law (militia obligation, tribunal attendance) as separate but overlapping systems administered by different offices. Before the Reforms, ward captains served as both commercial arbiters and militia commanders — concentrated authority producing inconsistent outcomes. The split created Midgaard's characteristic bureaucratic complexity — three offices potentially involved in any significant transaction — but also its accountability: each office's decisions are reviewable by the others. The Continuity faction treats the Reforms as the governance layer that made Midgaard stable enough to persist through subsequent crises. The Reckoning faction notes that the Reforms' district boundaries, combined with the Violet Compact's registry-primacy principle, created the administrative infrastructure for identifying and processing unregistered persons — the eventual condemned-debtor transfer mechanism. The lamp-lines' emergency signaling was repurposed during the Ash-and-Iron period as a population-tracking alert system: specific lantern sequences indicated which districts had unregistered persons requiring intake processing.

