Kowloon's Neon Covenant color system was partly influenced by Midgaard's Lantern Reforms, though Kowloon developed the concept significantly further. The Reforms used lanterns as administrative nodes and emergency signals; Kowloon's color-coding extended the same principle into every surface material, creating a city readable at a glance rather than only at posted notices. Kowloon's specific colors were drawn from the delta's existing material culture rather than from Midgaard's lamp-oil yellow standard. The Courier Lantern Office descended from the Lampkeeper tradition that predated even the Neon Covenant; the Reforms' lamp-line concept arrived in Kowloon as something the city was already doing in more sophisticated form. Kowloon views the Lantern Reforms as Midgaard's first serious attempt at governance legibility, and considers Midgaard's system still less readable than Kowloon's.

