Kiess's founding charter incorporated Lantern Reform infrastructure standards as the baseline for civic legibility, then extended them with formal accountability mechanisms. The extension was driven by Evermeet's failure: Evermeet had Lantern Reform-equivalent infrastructure but no formal mechanism for accountability when lamp-line decisions were contested. Kiess's charter requires every administrative node (lantern-station equivalent) to maintain a public record of the last five official decisions made at that node. The posted decision record was designed to prevent Violet Compact abuse: accumulation of sealed-warrant proceedings becomes visible as a pattern rather than remaining as individual acts obscured by procedure. Kiess's frontier risk doctrine holds that the Reforms were correct in principle but insufficient in scope: the lamp-lines' repurposing during the Ash-and-Iron years to identify districts with unregistered persons for intake processing is the specific case Kiess's anti-sealed-warrant doctrine was designed to prevent recurring.

