Rakuen's founding charter adopted Lantern Reform infrastructure standards as part of its institutional modeling on Midgaard's First Stone Accord governance tradition. The lamp-lines system was designed to be compatible with Midgaard's standards — explicit preparation for the annexation the founding generation expected. The Southmark Petition's ledger-compliance refusal prompted Rakuen to convert its accounting standards, bringing the ledger system into alignment with the Lantern Reform-era registry format. Rakuen's Bloom Pavilion serves the watched-square function: all civic proclamations, tribunal proceedings, and memorial readings occur there, following the First Stone Accord and Lantern Reform pattern of centralizing civic life at witnessed locations. The Compact Purist faction views successive adoptions of Midgaard standards as a pattern of institutional concession that yielded nothing; the Amendment Track faction views the same adoptions as evidence of compatibility Midgaard's constitutional argument does not acknowledge.

