The Lantern Reforms' posted tariff system is the closest Midgaard-tradition equivalent to Mafdet's harbor tariff boards. Mafdet's harbor tariff boards are more complex and more frequently updated: maritime cargo rates respond to seasonal conditions, route risk assessments, and commodity price fluctuations that the Reforms' fixed-rate system does not accommodate. The Strandline Compact's tariff framework was designed to be compatible with Lantern Reform-era trade documentation, so cargo moving from Mafdet's harbor into Midgaard's overland system could be documented in formats both cities' trade registries accepted. Mafdet views the Lantern Reforms as the governance layer that made Midgaard a reliable long-distance trade partner. The lamp-lines' emergency signaling function has no maritime analogue; cross-system incompatibility has caused coordination delays during multi-city emergencies.

